41:Even the (+1) and (+2) of Laplace's formula come back to haunt us if we take as our "best" estimate the center of a confidence interval at the 84 percent confidence level (Ref. [^1], Eq. 34.2.5). The person who, once aware of these things, still persists in saying that it is wrong to use the Bayes-Laplace methods and right to use confidence intervals, places himself in a very curious logical position. From a purely pragmatic standpoint, it is just impossible to see what all the shouting is about.
50:Similarly, the square of an efficient estimate of $\theta$ is not an efficient estimate of $\theta^2$; indeed, the very definition of efficiency (1) is parameter-dependent in such a way that if an efficient estimator of $\theta$ exists, then (Ref. [^1], p. 481) an efficient estimator of $\theta^2$ does not exist. If you find a shortest confidence interval for $\theta$, and a similar one for $\theta^2$, the two procedures will end up placing $\theta$ in different intervals.
